That's a great question!

The fastest animal on land is the **cheetah**, which can reach speeds of up to **70 miles per hour (113 kilometers per hour)** over short distances. However, this speed is only sustainable for about 20-30 seconds.

If we're talking about aquatic animals, the title of "fastest" is often debated between several species, including:

* The **sailfish**, which can reach speeds of up to **68 miles per hour (110 kilometers per hour)**.
* The **shortfin mako shark**, which has been clocked at **46 miles per hour (74 kilometers per hour)**.
* And the **bluefin tuna**, which can swim at speeds of up to **50 miles per hour (80 kilometers per hour)**.

But if we're talking about animals that can sustain their top speed over long distances, the title goes to the **peregrine falcon**, which can dive at speeds of up to **242 miles per hour (390 kilometers per hour)** during its characteristic hunting maneuver known as a stoop!

So, it really depends on how you define "fastest"!
